              'Grade 6-7': 'Delacroix constructs an elaborate comic performance in which stated criticism is systematically undermined by revealed affection. The opening declaration — "The English have no cuisine" — establishes a pose of Gallic superiority, reinforced by the tricolon of culinary horrors: vegetables that "surrender," meat like "upholstery," and puddings that sit "like ballast." Yet the register is playful rather than hostile; the personification of vegetables and the nautical metaphor of "ballast" signal wit, not contempt. The crucial pivot is the English breakfast paragraph, where the listing of components — bacon, sausages, beans, fried bread — accelerates into the magnificent simile of "a painter attacking a blank canvas," transforming chaos into art. The final three sentences enact the writer\'s confusion structurally: the short, declarative "I ate every morsel" confesses physical surrender, "It was magnificent" confesses intellectual surrender, and "I have been confused about English food ever since" admits that his own critical framework has been defeated by pleasure.',
