              'Grade 4-5': 'Both writers use humour to discuss food, but their perspectives are different. Liu argues that modern people have made food too complicated and stressful by moralising every choice, while Delacroix criticises English food for lacking sophistication but ultimately admits to enjoying it. Liu is concerned about the loss of simple pleasure in eating, while Delacroix discovers unexpected pleasure in food he expected to dislike. Both writers use lists — Liu lists ethical questions, Delacroix lists breakfast items — but for different effects: Liu\'s list overwhelms, while Delacroix\'s celebrates abundance.',
              'Grade 6-7': 'Both texts are fundamentally about the gap between what we think about food and how we experience it, but they approach this theme from opposite directions. Liu diagnoses a modern condition in which thinking about food has destroyed the pleasure of eating it; Delacroix enacts the reverse — his intellectual framework of French culinary superiority collapses when confronted with the physical pleasure of a full English breakfast. Both writers deploy humour as a persuasive strategy: Liu\'s escalating egg questions and Delacroix\'s "vegetables until they surrender" operate through similar mechanisms of comic exaggeration. However, Liu\'s humour serves a serious argumentative purpose (the moralisation thesis), while Delacroix\'s is more performative and self-deprecating. Structurally, both texts pivot on a reversal: Liu concedes ethical concerns before reasserting her point, while Delacroix\'s criticism of English food collapses into admiration. The most interesting convergence is in their conclusions: Liu\'s observation that caring most means enjoying least, and Delacroix\'s admission of being "confused," both suggest that the relationship between thought and pleasure is inherently paradoxical.',
