              'Grade 6-7': 'Both writers position themselves against the fashion industry, but their critiques operate in fundamentally different registers and historical contexts. Osei\'s argument is systemic and data-driven: the problem is an economic structure that hides costs ("polluted rivers, exhausted workers"), and the solution requires collective change. Worthington\'s argument is individual and moral: the problem is personal weakness in the face of novelty, and the solution is "consistency" of taste. Yet beneath these surface differences lies a shared conviction: both writers distinguish between genuine value and manufactured desire. Osei\'s contrast between a garment\'s price (£4.99) and its true cost (two hundred years of landfill) mirrors Worthington\'s distinction between fashion as "art" and fashion as "tyranny." Both writers use humour to expose absurdity — Osei\'s T-shirt-versus-sandwich comparison and Worthington\'s sleeve-catching-fire image serve identical rhetorical functions. The most instructive comparison is methodological: Osei builds from statistics to moral argument, while Worthington builds from moral principle to practical example, suggesting that the relationship between evidence and values in persuasive writing can be productively reversed.',
